Great.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:11.279
Then, yeah, I'll start with an introduction of myself.

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:14.279
I've been at Pratt & Whitney for a relatively short time,

00:02:14.279 --> 00:02:16.559
about one and a half years now.

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:19.119
I was hired initially as a contractor,

00:02:19.119 --> 00:02:20.960
so through a contracting agency,

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:23.320
to develop a forecasting model,

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:27.520
and from there transitioned to a role on the strategy team

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:32.000
where my current focus is on the strategy side

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.039
of decision analytics at Pratt & Whitney.

00:02:36.039 --> 00:02:40.320
In this presentation, I'm going to provide an overview

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:42.639
of two of the tools that I developed at Pratt

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:45.679
using R and RStudio Connect,

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:49.440
and then go into a few of the lessons learned

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:54.000
in my strategy role that apply, of course, directly to Pratt,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:01.320
but I'm sure apply broadly to other large companies as well.

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:04.240
So starting off, the first tool I'm going to talk about

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.720
is an engine repair forecasting model.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:10.800
This is the first tool that I worked on at Pratt,

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:12.919
and a brief background of Pratt & Whitney

00:03:12.919 --> 00:03:14.559
for those of you not familiar.

00:03:14.639 --> 00:03:16.759
According to Wikipedia, Pratt & Whitney

00:03:16.759 --> 00:03:21.440
is an aerospace manufacturer with global service operations,

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:23.839
and, you know, what that means is we manufacture

00:03:23.839 --> 00:03:26.759
and repair military and commercial engines,

00:03:26.759 --> 00:03:28.720
and my role throughout my whole time at Pratt

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:30.119
has been focused on the commercial

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:31.600
aftermarket side of the business,

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:33.000
which includes maintenance, repair,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.880
and overhaul of all of our engines.

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:38.520
So one of the biggest questions that we focus on

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:42.320
on this side of the company is how many engines

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.600
can our global network of repair shops

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:48.360
repair in the upcoming year?

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:52.440
This question is important because the repair shops

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:54.679
are giving annual and monthly repair goals

00:03:54.679 --> 00:03:57.279
that their performance is evaluated against,

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:00.600
and throughout this planning process,

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.960
any shortfalls that are identified

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:04.759
then lead to a lot of the work

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:06.000
that goes on throughout the year,

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.559
from investing in new repair technology,

00:04:10.559 --> 00:04:14.279
capacity constraints, and making decisions

00:04:14.279 --> 00:04:16.799
to reallocate engines across the network.

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:21.440
This question is also a complex question.

00:04:22.279 --> 00:04:25.200
Repair performance and the number of engines

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.480
that our entire network can repair

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:30.079
is influenced by many interacting variables,

00:04:30.079 --> 00:04:32.679
such as the type of repair being performed,

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:36.119
the turnaround time of each individual repair,

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:39.000
the capacity, not only at the shops themselves,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.399
but within the different sections of each shop,

00:04:43.399 --> 00:04:46.640
and existing work progress and backlogs.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.359
So not an easy question to answer.

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:51.079
Excuse me.

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:54.600
The current state, I guess before I move on to the solution,

00:04:56.519 --> 00:04:58.799
the current state that was in place

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:02.839
to answer this question was largely done

00:05:02.839 --> 00:05:05.320
by taking the previous year's numbers

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.320
and increasing and decreasing that amount

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.079
based on knowledge of changes in the business,

00:05:10.079 --> 00:05:11.839
conversations with the general managers

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:13.480
at all the repair shops.

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:18.480
What lacked was a rigorous quantified justification

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:19.600
behind these numbers.

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:25.920
And so what Pratt wanted was to make an answer

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.200
to this question more robust and defendable

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:31.200
by giving it a quantified justification.

00:05:32.839 --> 00:05:35.399
So the solution that I developed

00:05:35.399 --> 00:05:37.880
that helps answer this question

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:42.880
is a simulation-based forecasting model using R

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:46.279
that has been hosted on RStudio Connect.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:48.760
So what this model does

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:51.720
is it takes our global network of repair shops

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:53.519
and models the flow of engines

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:55.239
from the wing of the airplane

00:05:55.239 --> 00:05:57.600
through each stage of the repair journey

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.160
all the way through the delivery to customer

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:03.079
using a Markov decision process.

00:06:03.079 --> 00:06:04.880
So the diagram on the right,

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:06.200
I know the text is small

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:08.119
and it's not really meant to be read,

00:06:08.119 --> 00:06:13.119
but it shows how the process is mapped out at a high level

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:18.239
where each stage of the repair journey is given a state

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:22.920
and then the flow of the engines from state to state

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.160
is then governed by rules.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:29.279
And those rules are all dependent

00:06:29.279 --> 00:06:34.279
on a large number of inputs from the turnaround time.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:38.440
So the capacity of the shops to the work in progress

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:40.040
to the induction plan,

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:42.519
to the engines currently sitting outside the shop

00:06:42.519 --> 00:06:44.119
and backlog.

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:49.119
And so one thing this model allows Pratt to do now

00:06:50.679 --> 00:06:53.279
is instead of talking about it as a whole

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:55.600
and doing all that thinking in your head,

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:58.239
we can have focused conversations on individual inputs

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:00.559
like the capacity of this section of the shop,

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:03.079
has that increased or decreased?

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:04.160
The turnaround times,

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:05.640
are we expecting similar turnaround times

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:08.799
on these repairs this year as opposed to next year?

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:12.559
And then roll all of those inputs and conversations

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:15.399
up to the model,

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:20.160
which will then output a final number

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:22.040
for engines inducted and returned.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:28.040
So the main benefit is it offers a quantified justification

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:30.359
for annual and monthly repair goals.

00:07:30.359 --> 00:07:34.799
And then it also allows for sensitivity analysis

00:07:34.799 --> 00:07:36.040
and scenario testing.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:40.559
This has taken the shape of

00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:42.519
how does increasing the capacity of this shop

00:07:42.519 --> 00:07:45.279
actually impact the number of engines

00:07:45.279 --> 00:07:47.760
we get to repair as a whole.

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:48.760
Or scenario testing,

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:52.040
which came into play last year

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:54.399
as COVID hit the airline industry.

00:07:54.399 --> 00:07:56.239
We had to rapidly change our goals

00:07:56.239 --> 00:07:59.519
and adapt to a new environment,

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:02.200
new demand and new capacity

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:04.760
as a lot of our workforce was reduced.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.239
And so this model quickly allowed us

00:08:07.239 --> 00:08:10.920
to run many different scenarios in a short period of time,

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:15.839
which is something we weren't able to do before.

00:08:15.839 --> 00:08:19.799
The last benefit is having the graphical user interface

00:08:19.799 --> 00:08:22.679
on RStudio so that ultimately

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:24.839
I'm not the end user of this model

00:08:24.839 --> 00:08:27.279
and the end user of this model

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:31.600
doesn't have strong background in R

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:34.719
and can operate and use the model

00:08:34.719 --> 00:08:37.520
through RStudio Connect and the graphic user interface.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.880
A few screenshots to show you what it looks like

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:44.280
and what that interface is like.

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:46.599
I'll highlight a few things here.

00:08:46.599 --> 00:08:49.239
And these are four of the main screens.

00:08:49.239 --> 00:08:50.760
The only thing not shown here

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:53.679
is the ability to then download the raw data output

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:56.520
for any analysis that isn't displayed here.

00:08:56.520 --> 00:08:59.919
But these four screens answer most of the common questions

00:08:59.919 --> 00:09:01.359
that Pratt is interested in,

00:09:01.359 --> 00:09:05.960
namely, what are the annual inductions

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:08.599
into our repair shops and what are the annual returns?

00:09:08.599 --> 00:09:10.239
What's the comparison to plan?

00:09:12.119 --> 00:09:14.599
And where there is backlog,

00:09:14.599 --> 00:09:16.159
there's a page that then drills down

00:09:16.159 --> 00:09:19.000
and shows each individual engine that's being modeled,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.559
where the backlog occurred

00:09:20.559 --> 00:09:22.400
and what could be done to address it.

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:28.000
The next tool that I'm gonna talk about

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.080
is a WIP management tool.

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:32.520
WIP stands for work in progress

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:35.359
and it's the term we use to describe

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:39.880
the engines currently in our repair shop.

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:44.559
So this model came about from,

00:09:44.559 --> 00:09:47.119
or this project came about from conversations

00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:49.400
with one of our specific repair shops.

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:52.840
When an engine is received,

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:55.799
a repair shop signs the contract with a promise date

00:09:55.799 --> 00:09:59.159
at which the engine will be returned to the customer.

00:09:59.159 --> 00:10:03.679
And the biggest issue at this shop was late deliveries.

00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:05.400
Their number one customer complaint

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:08.200
was that promise dates couldn't be trusted

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:09.760
and this impacted their brand.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:12.520
And so their question, their problem to me

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:15.000
was how can the number of late deliveries,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.200
that is repairs taking longer than promised

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:19.039
to the customer, be reduced?

00:10:20.039 --> 00:10:24.039
I talked a little bit about the importance of this,

00:10:24.039 --> 00:10:27.359
but when an engine is not delivered to the customer

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:28.599
on the date that they promised,

00:10:28.599 --> 00:10:30.000
it's difficult for the customers

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
to plan their business operations.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.640
And they've told this shop many times,

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:37.840
listen, it's okay if the promised date is later,

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:39.359
but we just need to know a date

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:41.119
so we can plan our operations.

00:10:41.119 --> 00:10:45.000
So that was one of the big important parts of this question.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.599
The other one is, of course,

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:48.559
the other one is, of course,

00:10:48.559 --> 00:10:51.200
as Pratt misses delivery dates,

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.520
it leaves a negative impact on our brand and reputation,

00:10:56.520 --> 00:10:59.039
which impacts our ability to win new contracts.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:03.119
The other important part of this question

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:07.719
is the issue that the shop faced

00:11:07.719 --> 00:11:11.760
was inefficient prioritization of their work in progress.

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:14.880
Because with the backlog that they had,

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:17.599
they found themselves focusing on parts and repairs

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:20.960
for customers that simply screamed the loudest,

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:25.039
which was described as a chaotic business process.

00:11:25.919 --> 00:11:30.039
And so the fundamental issue here was a lack of visibility.

00:11:30.039 --> 00:11:32.039
For a complete view or understanding

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:34.400
of what was in the shop at any given time,

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:37.559
it required a manual pull from different databases

00:11:37.559 --> 00:11:40.000
and a manual report build.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.640
And because of the labor and time-consuming nature

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:46.799
of this process, it was done once a day,

00:11:46.799 --> 00:11:49.799
and there still wasn't full visibility

00:11:49.799 --> 00:11:52.640
onto what engines were,

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:56.359
what parts were on hold with the engineering team

00:11:56.359 --> 00:12:00.200
without going around and investigating

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:01.719
on an engine-by-engine basis.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:06.960
The other issue that led to this problem

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:11.960
was there was no measure of repairs expected delivery date,

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:16.400
aside from intuition and judgment,

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:19.200
knowing where in the shop each part was,

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:20.719
but there was no quantified metric

00:12:20.719 --> 00:12:22.919
for repairs expected delivery date.

00:12:24.719 --> 00:12:29.719
So the solution developed here was a WIP overview dashboard

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.440
and forecasted repair completion date model.

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:38.919
What this dashboard did is it takes real-time

00:12:38.919 --> 00:12:40.640
work-in-progress progress,

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.200
so the real-time repair progress and hold data,

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:47.520
and it aggregates it and displays it on the dashboard.

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:50.080
So fundamentally, this is just a dashboard

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:52.799
that displays the current state of the shop.

00:12:55.479 --> 00:12:58.640
It has one analytical layer to it

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:00.919
that takes historical repair data

00:13:00.919 --> 00:13:04.039
and uses that to estimate turnaround times

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:08.039
and likelihoods of on-time delivery for current repairs.

00:13:08.039 --> 00:13:11.479
So one example here is a fan blade comes into the shop.

00:13:11.479 --> 00:13:13.440
Well, that fan blade with that type of damage

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:16.400
has been in the shop 50 times before,

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:20.440
and this chart here shows the actual

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:24.880
historical turnaround times of part and repair,

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:28.239
number A25343, so a repair that's been to the shop

00:13:28.239 --> 00:13:30.760
many times, and we have a good idea

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.200
of what the range of turnaround times are.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:35.599
So it uses that distribution then

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:38.760
to give an expected turnaround time,

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.239
an expected delivery date, and then the likelihood

00:13:41.239 --> 00:13:42.840
that it'll be delivered on time.

00:13:44.119 --> 00:13:45.799
Some screenshots from this tool.

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:50.159
I'll highlight a few things here.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:55.479
The forward pane here that has those four boxes,

00:13:55.479 --> 00:13:58.880
that gives the direct overview in green on the right

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:01.039
how many engines, how many repairs

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:04.599
are in the shop right now, how many of them are on hold,

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:06.880
how many of them cannot be touched

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:09.599
because they're waiting for input from the customer

00:14:09.599 --> 00:14:13.520
or our engineering team, and then how many

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:15.000
have missed the delivery date.

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:20.000
An important feature here is the bar chart

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:21.799
or the histogram you see there.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:25.960
An interesting trend that this makes clear

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:30.479
and highlights is how at the end of each month

00:14:30.479 --> 00:14:34.880
there's a surge in repairs that are due.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:37.919
So that first tall bar happens to be the last date

00:14:37.919 --> 00:14:40.679
of August when this screenshot was taken.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:43.919
And what this does is it gives, right up front,

00:14:43.919 --> 00:14:47.520
it gives the repair shop general manager

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:49.400
and the cell leads a clear view

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:51.200
of what's coming down the pipeline.

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:54.679
And just that visibility alone helps drive

00:14:54.679 --> 00:14:57.000
the prioritization and the behavior needed

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.200
to minimize those missed delivery dates.

00:15:01.359 --> 00:15:04.479
Also included in this tool in the second pane here

00:15:04.479 --> 00:15:08.919
is a drill down into the individual repairs

00:15:08.919 --> 00:15:11.919
where information can be seen on their progress.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:19.679
So moving on to my role in the strategy team

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:21.559
is I've kind of taken a step back

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:25.799
from the individual tools and taken a higher level view

00:15:25.799 --> 00:15:30.799
and trying to work on ways that Pratt can prioritize

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:35.640
decision analytics projects and best use them.

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:37.400
And one framework that's helped me think

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:40.960
about these projects is the decision analytics hierarchy

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:45.320
of needs based loosely off Maslow's hierarchy of needs.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:49.840
The idea here being each level of the pyramid

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:51.679
needs to be addressed before the other one

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:53.559
can even be worked on.

00:15:53.559 --> 00:15:55.679
And the way I've broken it down

00:15:55.679 --> 00:15:57.880
and the way I see a lot of projects at Pratt

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:04.000
are data storage and organization is the first step

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:08.080
and the most important step that needs to be addressed.

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:13.080
Data relevant to your project or your business need

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:15.799
needs to be stored and organized

00:16:15.799 --> 00:16:19.640
in an effective and thoughtful way.

00:16:20.640 --> 00:16:23.400
However, storage and organization is not enough.

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:27.880
There then needs to be data accessibility in place.

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:29.559
So what's required to make the data

00:16:29.559 --> 00:16:31.400
accessible to stakeholders?

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:36.400
That could be literal access, access approval,

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:42.520
having the credentials or tools

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:44.320
you need to access the database.

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:47.320
But it also means is it stored in a way that is accessible?

00:16:47.719 --> 00:16:52.719
Is it in, there's a team here that has a lot

00:16:53.159 --> 00:16:55.479
of repair information stored in PDFs.

00:16:55.479 --> 00:16:57.640
Well, it's stored, but it's not accessible

00:16:57.640 --> 00:16:58.719
in a meaningful way.

00:17:02.039 --> 00:17:06.680
The last step then is when you have successful data storage

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:11.079
and accessibility is then building the analytics tools

00:17:11.079 --> 00:17:13.920
and then implementing data-driven decisions.

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:17.199
So how can the data then be used to serve our needs

00:17:17.199 --> 00:17:19.199
and make better decisions?

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:22.400
A lot of times there's a lot of talk and focus

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:25.599
on the top of the pyramid without full understanding

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:28.560
and focus on data accessibility and data storage.

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:31.839
So this is a framework that I find useful

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:36.839
to level set expectations for a project

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.760
and then direct the right resources

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.640
to the right problems before starting a project.

00:17:44.839 --> 00:17:48.160
And then this last slide here are some common challenges

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.680
that I've faced during my time at Pratt

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:52.839
and I'm sure are not specific to Pratt.

00:17:54.439 --> 00:17:58.199
I also talk about some of the approaches

00:17:58.199 --> 00:18:02.760
that we've taken here to address these issues.

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:04.520
They're by no means the right answer

00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:07.239
or even the only right answer

00:18:07.239 --> 00:18:09.760
or even complete answers to the problems,

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:12.640
but they are steps that we've taken that have helped us.

00:18:14.079 --> 00:18:16.280
So one of the biggest common challenges

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:19.040
is lack of engagement from all stakeholders.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:21.520
And I see I'm running a bit short on time,

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:24.239
so I will rattle through this somewhat quickly,

00:18:24.239 --> 00:18:29.239
but there's two main cases that we've identified

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:32.839
or I've noticed here,

00:18:32.839 --> 00:18:34.680
and that's analytics tools developed

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:36.719
without enough input from the end user.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:41.719
This usually means or results in the business needs

00:18:41.719 --> 00:18:44.199
not being addressed by the tool directly

00:18:44.199 --> 00:18:46.959
and ultimate ownership and integration

00:18:46.959 --> 00:18:49.160
of the tool into business processes

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:50.760
becomes unclear and difficult.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.760
The other type of issue of lack of engagement

00:18:55.760 --> 00:18:59.760
from all stakeholders is analytics tools being developed

00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:02.520
by the business users, in our case, the repair shops

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:05.479
without involvement of the central technology team.

00:19:07.119 --> 00:19:10.280
This usually leads to fragile and fragmented architecture,

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:15.160
manual data transfer, copying of Excel files and CSV files

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:18.319
and an inefficient use of resources.

00:19:19.479 --> 00:19:21.479
Two ways that we've addressed this

00:19:21.479 --> 00:19:24.079
and we are working to address these issues

00:19:24.079 --> 00:19:27.880
are to involve the business user more.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.599
For both of these, you need to approach these problems

00:19:32.599 --> 00:19:34.359
and these situations with the intention

00:19:34.359 --> 00:19:36.239
of bringing the stakeholders together.

00:19:36.239 --> 00:19:38.040
To involve the business user more,

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:41.359
the design needs to be centered around the business need.

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:47.239
Then effort needs to be put in to develop

00:19:47.239 --> 00:19:50.359
and implement a minimum viable product

00:19:50.359 --> 00:19:53.199
and then iterate and increase investment over time

00:19:54.239 --> 00:19:56.119
all the while incorporating feedback

00:19:56.119 --> 00:19:57.400
to meet the business need.

00:19:59.959 --> 00:20:04.199
Finally, or secondly,

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:08.920
to encourage the business users

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:11.719
to involve the digital technology team,

00:20:11.719 --> 00:20:13.800
regular communications to understand business needs

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:15.760
and capabilities should be established.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:17.959
We did this in the form of phone calls

00:20:17.959 --> 00:20:22.800
to all our repair sites to understand their needs

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:25.119
and talk about our capabilities.

00:20:25.119 --> 00:20:27.880
And then the big thing here is organic involvement

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:32.400
of the digital technology team through a series of successes.

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:35.640
So have the business users organically

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:37.199
come to the digital technology team

00:20:37.199 --> 00:20:40.199
because you've delivered value in the past.

00:20:40.199 --> 00:20:45.199
The last issue is one that I'm sure many organizations face

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:48.640
and that's inefficient allocation of limited resources.

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:51.560
So there's limited funding and limited hours in the day.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:57.400
The obvious answer here that has existed

00:20:57.400 --> 00:21:00.280
but sometimes isn't always used here at Pratt

00:21:00.280 --> 00:21:03.359
is developing prioritization methodologies.

00:21:03.359 --> 00:21:04.959
So that's taking a step back,

00:21:04.959 --> 00:21:07.920
clearly defining strategic organizational goals

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:10.880
and then designing a resource allocation process

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:15.439
that stimulates and promotes conversation

00:21:15.439 --> 00:21:16.959
on how these projects align

00:21:16.959 --> 00:21:18.839
to the strategic organizational goals.

00:21:19.959 --> 00:21:24.599
All right, I will stop there and pause for any questions.

00:21:24.599 --> 00:21:26.040
I hope I didn't go over time.

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:30.319
Oh, you were great, Brennan, thank you.

00:21:30.319 --> 00:21:34.199
I do know we have quite a bit to go through for an hour.

00:21:34.199 --> 00:21:36.439
So I may put some of the questions

00:21:36.439 --> 00:21:38.880
to the chat window initially, if that's okay.

00:21:40.119 --> 00:21:44.280
Brennan, I know one question Jeff just asked

00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:48.119
is for data storage, what solutions or technologies

00:21:48.119 --> 00:21:49.760
are you currently using?

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:53.479
If you wouldn't mind answering that one in the chat too.

00:21:53.839 --> 00:21:57.880
Totally, oh, answer in the chat or answer it?

00:21:57.880 --> 00:21:59.839
Or we can answer that one quickly now.

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:02.160
Okay, I'll answer that one quickly

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.760
and then other ones in the chat.

00:22:03.760 --> 00:22:08.760
But data storage, the biggest tool that we use is SAP.

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:12.560
And that has all of our repair data

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:16.319
and really all the data that's needed,

00:22:16.319 --> 00:22:19.319
most of the data that's needed to build these tools.

00:22:19.319 --> 00:22:21.359
The one interesting thing I'll comment on that

00:22:21.359 --> 00:22:26.359
is SAP is set up for us at least in a way that it is,

00:22:29.520 --> 00:22:32.479
all the resources at SAP are used to store the data

00:22:32.479 --> 00:22:34.839
and you can't connect directly to SAP.

00:22:34.839 --> 00:22:39.000
So we've developed other database tools

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:43.199
that for the sole purpose of bringing the data from SAP

00:22:43.199 --> 00:22:46.199
on a periodic basis and then making that

00:22:46.199 --> 00:22:48.719
as an Oracle database, Hadoop is another tool

00:22:48.719 --> 00:22:51.239
that we've used to connect directly to SAP.

00:22:51.959 --> 00:22:55.359
So you can't connect directly to the data.

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:58.719
The big reason there is it's resource intensive

00:22:58.719 --> 00:23:00.439
to pull from SAP.

00:23:00.439 --> 00:23:02.280
So you have one tool that does that

00:23:02.280 --> 00:23:05.400
and then that becomes the source for a lot of other tools.

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:08.400
Awesome, thank you so much, Brendan.

00:23:09.640 --> 00:23:12.040
For our second presentation,

00:23:12.040 --> 00:23:15.040
I'd love to turn it over to Philip Lear as well.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:18.040
So Philip is a Principal Data Scientist

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:19.520
at the Kellogg Company.

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:24.359
And your share there, Brendan, there we go.

00:23:24.359 --> 00:23:27.119
And I think, Phil, you should be able to share now.

00:23:33.839 --> 00:23:37.800
And again, please ask any questions through the chat too

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:40.680
and we'll follow up with the presenters after

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:42.560
and I'll put that on community too.

00:23:43.719 --> 00:23:44.560
Thanks, Phil.

00:23:45.599 --> 00:23:46.719
Can you see my screen

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:49.719
and are you seeing the right presentation?

00:23:49.719 --> 00:23:51.239
Sorry, I'm using multiple monitors

00:23:51.239 --> 00:23:53.319
and I always get confused.

00:23:53.319 --> 00:23:54.160
Yes, we can see.

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:55.839
What do you see versus what I see, okay.

00:23:55.839 --> 00:23:57.040
We can see it.

00:23:57.040 --> 00:23:59.319
So like she said, I'm the Principal Data Scientist

00:23:59.319 --> 00:24:00.959
at the Kellogg Company.

00:24:02.199 --> 00:24:04.680
I've assumed most people are fairly familiar with Kellogg,

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:07.239
but just as a brief history,

00:24:07.239 --> 00:24:09.839
we are a 115-year-old food company.

00:24:11.719 --> 00:24:14.160
The slide kind of shows the timeline.

00:24:15.199 --> 00:24:17.160
What I'd like you to get out of this is that

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:20.959
on the left, you sort of see these great brands

00:24:20.959 --> 00:24:24.640
and historic development of sales and marketing techniques

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:25.560
and all that.

00:24:25.560 --> 00:24:29.760
That is sort of like the first part of Kellogg's history.

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:31.520
Most of this probably took place before

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:34.599
there were IT departments or,

00:24:34.599 --> 00:24:36.599
certainly analytics departments.

00:24:36.599 --> 00:24:38.359
But in the middle, you start to see

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:43.920
where IT starts to play an important role.

00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:45.000
So in the seventies,

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:46.680
we acquire a frozen waffle company.

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:51.680
It's very different than shelf-stable cereal.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:53.560
2000, we acquire Poshy.

00:24:53.560 --> 00:24:55.359
This is an entirely different supply chain

00:24:55.359 --> 00:24:57.000
because it's natural and organic.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:57.959
New set of customers.

00:24:57.959 --> 00:25:00.359
2001, we acquire Keebler,

00:25:00.359 --> 00:25:03.239
which is a giant snacks company in its own right.

00:25:03.239 --> 00:25:06.400
They actually use something called direct store delivery

00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:08.239
as their distribution model,

00:25:08.239 --> 00:25:10.719
which means the employees

00:25:10.719 --> 00:25:13.000
who are the people who drive the trucks

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.599
and the trucks are assets and the logistics are managed.

00:25:16.599 --> 00:25:21.239
So the amount of data generated by a Keebler cookie

00:25:21.239 --> 00:25:23.319
from factory to the store shelf

00:25:23.319 --> 00:25:26.319
is significantly more than a box of Frosted Flakes would have.

00:25:27.239 --> 00:25:30.800
We actually had to adopt Keebler's ERP system

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:33.079
because what Kellogg had at the time couldn't handle it.

00:25:33.079 --> 00:25:36.719
Pringles is a massive global supply chain.

00:25:36.719 --> 00:25:40.719
In 2015, we expanded to Africa and Egypt with major brands.

00:25:40.760 --> 00:25:42.839
2017, RX Bar is acquired,

00:25:42.839 --> 00:25:44.719
which is a new set of customers

00:25:44.719 --> 00:25:46.839
and primarily through e-commerce.

00:25:46.839 --> 00:25:49.880
And then in 2019, we actually spun off the cookie

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:52.800
and fruit snacks and ingredients business of Keebler

00:25:54.479 --> 00:25:55.800
and sold it to Ferrero.

00:25:56.680 --> 00:25:59.640
My hypothesis would be that the right side

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:03.800
is sort of enabled by IT and analytics,

00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:06.040
but it's still a 115-year-old company

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:08.199
and there were still a number of challenges we've had.

00:26:08.199 --> 00:26:09.800
I started in 2010,

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.760
for, if you need some reference,

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:16.239
TikTok by Kesha was the number one song.

00:26:16.239 --> 00:26:18.920
I honestly don't think I know any of these songs.

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:20.880
I was surprised when I looked these up.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:25.520
But our ecosystem at Kellogg for analytics,

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:27.280
and keep in mind, we have SAP,

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:28.880
we have all these other things,

00:26:30.599 --> 00:26:34.839
the reporting at the company was well-established,

00:26:34.839 --> 00:26:36.680
but analytics was sort of niche.

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:40.680
Everything was sort of segmented.

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:43.000
IT had its own thing.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.839
Analytics was primarily in the business,

00:26:44.839 --> 00:26:46.239
either marketing or sales.

00:26:49.040 --> 00:26:51.800
We had our own network of servers,

00:26:51.800 --> 00:26:53.520
which by that I mean,

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:56.479
we had desktops that sat under our desks

00:26:56.479 --> 00:26:58.560
and had RAID drives attached to them.

00:26:59.439 --> 00:27:02.040
And if a hard drive or a fan failed

00:27:02.040 --> 00:27:03.959
on one of these RAID drives,

00:27:03.959 --> 00:27:05.439
there were more than one occasion

00:27:05.439 --> 00:27:07.280
where I actually went to Best Buy

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:09.319
to go buy a new hard drive.

00:27:09.319 --> 00:27:12.000
We had a little toolbox and we unscrewed the plates

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:13.479
and pull the drives out.

00:27:13.479 --> 00:27:17.880
Very, very, very, very sort of guerrilla analytics team

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:19.400
at the time.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:21.119
The desktop SAS license,

00:27:22.040 --> 00:27:24.400
desktop R and Python, obviously.

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:27.160
We could not touch SAP at all.

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:29.439
So any data we needed to get from SAP

00:27:29.439 --> 00:27:31.800
traditionally had to go into a transfer server.

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:33.959
And then it was sort of like this Rube Goldberg machine

00:27:33.959 --> 00:27:37.199
of how to get data from one place to the next.

00:27:37.199 --> 00:27:40.640
And then probably the worst part to me

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:42.479
coming out of grad school was

00:27:42.479 --> 00:27:44.640
everything that was a deliverable

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:47.160
was effectively in Excel or Python

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:48.839
or Excel or PowerPoint, sorry.

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:51.400
And I was an econ grad.

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:54.920
I hadn't really ever used either one of those

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:56.680
to be completely honest.

00:27:56.680 --> 00:28:00.560
So in the first few years of my time at Kellogg,

00:28:00.560 --> 00:28:03.880
I think I wrote more VBA code

00:28:05.079 --> 00:28:06.839
than most people probably would ever write in a lifetime

00:28:06.839 --> 00:28:08.439
because they'd want simulations

00:28:08.439 --> 00:28:10.520
and some of these other things.

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:12.479
The downside of all that was that

00:28:12.479 --> 00:28:14.280
if you build a tool in Excel

00:28:15.319 --> 00:28:16.680
and you gave it to somebody,

00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:20.239
there was zero chance of ever updating any of the data

00:28:20.239 --> 00:28:23.160
or any of the methods or anything in those tools.

00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:24.560
So over the next few years,

00:28:25.839 --> 00:28:29.479
we really focused on how we got data.

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:35.560
How we delivered sort of these data products to people.

00:28:37.319 --> 00:28:39.680
If anyone who I work with is watching this,

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:42.920
they may disagree with how nice and neat these lines look,

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:44.560
but it was certainly an improvement

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:47.640
over what we had when we started.

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.359
We'd moved to a SAS server,

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:55.280
effectively let people share code and compute time

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:57.079
and all these things across the network.

00:28:57.079 --> 00:28:59.319
We had SharePoint to sort of deliver PowerPoint

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:03.160
in Excel to people versus sending mass emails.

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:04.160
This helps a little

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:06.880
in that we can replace a version on SharePoint,

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:11.239
but obviously if someone copies, takes a copy,

00:29:11.239 --> 00:29:12.760
there's no way to update that.

00:29:13.959 --> 00:29:16.040
We got a Tableau server,

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:17.880
which I think reduced some of the PowerPoints,

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:22.880
but people were stretching the limits of Tableau

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:24.839
and what it could do.

00:29:24.839 --> 00:29:28.079
So we set up some .NET servers

00:29:28.079 --> 00:29:29.920
where people could build custom applications

00:29:29.920 --> 00:29:31.040
and tie them in to,

00:29:33.439 --> 00:29:35.319
short procedures could act on databases

00:29:35.319 --> 00:29:38.000
or you could run a SAS for procedure.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:38.839
It's hard to do these things,

00:29:38.839 --> 00:29:43.560
but there's a fair amount of bureaucracy

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:46.280
you'd have to go through to get through these.

00:29:46.280 --> 00:29:50.119
So in 2018, there was a push

00:29:51.959 --> 00:29:56.359
that I think what people said is cloud first,

00:29:56.359 --> 00:30:00.000
mobile first, API first was sort of an IT rallying cry.

00:30:00.959 --> 00:30:02.760
The majority of the analytics people

00:30:02.760 --> 00:30:05.280
had been moved into IT by this time.

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:09.920
We had multiple servers.

00:30:09.920 --> 00:30:14.160
We stood up a number of database management systems

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:15.079
that people could access

00:30:15.079 --> 00:30:18.520
depending upon the level of skill they needed access to.

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:21.400
And in 2018, I was just sort of sent

00:30:21.400 --> 00:30:23.959
on endless amounts of conferences

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:27.280
as we approached building the strategy.

00:30:27.280 --> 00:30:29.119
And there are a lot of them that were

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:33.839
less valuable than others.

00:30:33.839 --> 00:30:35.839
Just by happenstance in 2018,

00:30:35.839 --> 00:30:37.319
there was this conference called URL,

00:30:37.319 --> 00:30:39.800
which is the enterprise application of the R language.

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:43.119
Apparently it's not normally in the US.

00:30:43.119 --> 00:30:45.439
So this was sort of a special occasion

00:30:45.439 --> 00:30:47.599
and I grabbed a couple of people on the team

00:30:47.599 --> 00:30:51.640
and we went to this and I loved it.

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:54.280
I mean, it was awesome to hear people

00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:57.199
talking about using R and open source

00:30:57.199 --> 00:30:58.920
sort of in a production environment

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:00.839
and enterprise environment.

00:31:00.839 --> 00:31:03.560
I think our studio had a small table there

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:06.199
and it was Thomas Mock actually, I remember this.

00:31:06.199 --> 00:31:08.800
And whoever he was with,

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:11.479
he got grilled for like two hours

00:31:11.479 --> 00:31:14.199
by me and an engineer I brought

00:31:14.199 --> 00:31:16.359
and one of the other people on our team

00:31:16.359 --> 00:31:18.239
on what Connect did.

00:31:18.239 --> 00:31:20.520
Because we were effectively going through

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:23.119
the idea of like what we were building

00:31:23.119 --> 00:31:26.319
to deliver this cloud-based architecture for analytics.

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:33.160
A couple of months later, our studio conference is in Austin.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:34.839
We go to that as well.

00:31:34.839 --> 00:31:37.000
And again, Thomas Mock is there

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.400
and I accost him and talk to him.

00:31:39.400 --> 00:31:41.959
And I told him I was actually skipping.

00:31:41.959 --> 00:31:44.319
I teach at a university,

00:31:44.319 --> 00:31:46.479
teach an honors class that Econ students

00:31:46.479 --> 00:31:47.800
effectively teach them how to use R

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:51.640
in sort of real world applications for econometrics.

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:54.479
And I told him I was skipping this

00:31:54.479 --> 00:31:56.040
and I was teaching.

00:31:56.040 --> 00:31:56.959
So they got a week off,

00:31:56.959 --> 00:31:59.760
but I was gonna come back and share all this with them.

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:02.119
And he told me about RStudio Cloud,

00:32:02.119 --> 00:32:03.760
which was in beta at the time.

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:08.239
So I went back, end of January,

00:32:08.239 --> 00:32:09.400
I go back, I start teaching

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:13.000
and I attempt to switch all of these juniors and seniors

00:32:14.119 --> 00:32:15.839
onto using a cloud platform.

00:32:15.959 --> 00:32:17.680
Remember, these are college kids.

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:19.640
They don't really know,

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:21.920
they're econ major college kids.

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:23.839
They don't really know much about this stuff.

00:32:23.839 --> 00:32:25.520
So I had sort of one experiment going

00:32:25.520 --> 00:32:29.599
with this cloud-based analytics with my students.

00:32:29.599 --> 00:32:30.439
And then we came back,

00:32:30.439 --> 00:32:32.400
we started really looking into things.

00:32:32.400 --> 00:32:36.760
Prior to this, we looked at the usual suspects,

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:38.359
the anacondas.

00:32:38.359 --> 00:32:43.359
And I think one of our engineers built Zeppelin

00:32:43.719 --> 00:32:48.319
which is Apache's sort of version of a notebook,

00:32:48.319 --> 00:32:50.719
but it's based on the Java runtime environment.

00:32:50.719 --> 00:32:52.119
I think it was the first time I ever saw someone

00:32:52.119 --> 00:32:54.599
sort of get booed when they presented something

00:32:54.599 --> 00:32:59.359
because the data scientists at the time

00:32:59.359 --> 00:33:04.359
didn't really wanna learn Java to run their notebook.

00:33:04.359 --> 00:33:07.640
So what I'm gonna go through now

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:11.439
is sort of a story in three acts,

00:33:11.439 --> 00:33:12.439
two parts each act.

00:33:12.439 --> 00:33:13.520
Three things we did well

00:33:13.520 --> 00:33:16.160
and then three things we could have done better.

00:33:18.719 --> 00:33:22.640
So the first thing we did is set up these test environments.

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:25.199
Like I said, we tried multiple environments.

00:33:25.199 --> 00:33:27.839
We, I think we somehow provisioned some servers

00:33:27.839 --> 00:33:30.319
and started setting all these little tests up

00:33:30.319 --> 00:33:31.920
and doing things.

00:33:31.920 --> 00:33:34.880
Because as we were having a conversation with IT,

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:36.520
which is a fair amount of IT people

00:33:36.520 --> 00:33:39.560
are like finance managers, program managers.

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:41.839
Everyone was very, very interested

00:33:41.839 --> 00:33:42.719
in switching to open source,

00:33:42.719 --> 00:33:43.560
which is very odd to me.

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:46.479
So I started and I talked about R, Python.

00:33:47.800 --> 00:33:49.119
Most of the time people thought

00:33:49.119 --> 00:33:50.319
there was some security risks

00:33:50.319 --> 00:33:52.959
using open source software.

00:33:53.839 --> 00:33:54.800
But somewhere along the line,

00:33:54.800 --> 00:33:55.719
there was a change of heart.

00:33:55.719 --> 00:33:57.199
I come to find out this is mostly

00:33:57.199 --> 00:33:59.800
because they thought open source meant free.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:01.439
Like they thought that switching to R

00:34:01.439 --> 00:34:03.520
would mean like total cost of ownership

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:06.119
would go down substantially.

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:09.040
And it was very difficult to say,

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:11.560
to explain to people why we would need this architecture,

00:34:11.560 --> 00:34:15.600
why we would want a product like RStudio Connect.

00:34:15.600 --> 00:34:18.760
So we just built our own version of,

00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:20.959
you know, as close to RStudio Connect as we could get.

00:34:20.959 --> 00:34:24.399
We built, you know, RStudio Pro server.

00:34:24.399 --> 00:34:26.719
We built a hosting environment for Shiny applications

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:28.199
and Markdown applications.

00:34:28.199 --> 00:34:30.639
And we started converting some of the existing projects

00:34:30.639 --> 00:34:34.080
we had into R and deploying them through Shiny.

00:34:35.280 --> 00:34:37.479
You know, we set up, I think we had a Git lab

00:34:38.479 --> 00:34:39.959
that we installed on one of the servers

00:34:39.959 --> 00:34:42.159
and started, really built the entire ecosystem

00:34:42.159 --> 00:34:43.120
to show people how it worked

00:34:43.120 --> 00:34:45.280
and kind of prove out, you know,

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:47.080
our vision of what this cloud-based

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:49.159
analytic system would look like.

00:34:49.159 --> 00:34:50.600
And it was pretty successful.

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:55.080
Now, unfortunately, what we didn't do

00:34:55.080 --> 00:34:58.399
was sort of plan for the long-term management of this.

00:34:58.399 --> 00:35:01.080
So we stood up the RStudio server

00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:03.040
and we got people accounts.

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:04.479
We had all this, we had the POC,

00:35:04.479 --> 00:35:07.800
we had project managers, we had all these things, right?

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:08.840
And then once it was a success,

00:35:08.840 --> 00:35:10.959
everyone said, yeah, this is successful.

00:35:10.959 --> 00:35:14.000
And then they sort of handed the keys over to our team.

00:35:15.879 --> 00:35:18.040
And while it was, I mean, it was certainly interesting

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.080
because me and another person on my team

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:23.919
started actually approving, you know,

00:35:23.919 --> 00:35:26.560
approving the requests for licenses

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:28.199
and setting them up on the server

00:35:28.199 --> 00:35:30.120
and, you know, writing back code

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:32.080
to handle updates and all these things.

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:36.360
That really wasn't the best time for our people.

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:41.360
So now we've sort of hired some people

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:44.840
who are full-time managers of the system.

00:35:44.840 --> 00:35:49.280
They can, you know, the compiler needs to be updated.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:51.560
They can update the compiler if, you know,

00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:53.760
we need to expand or buy more space,

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:55.879
whatever, they're sort of managing this stuff.

00:35:57.639 --> 00:35:58.919
It was a good problem to have.

00:35:58.919 --> 00:36:00.040
It became very successful

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:03.040
and it sort of overwhelmed us

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:04.679
in how much work needs to be done

00:36:04.679 --> 00:36:06.360
to maintain and add people.

00:36:07.679 --> 00:36:10.399
But in retrospect, it would have been ideal

00:36:10.399 --> 00:36:12.959
if we would have thought all this out ahead of time.

00:36:15.399 --> 00:36:18.159
The second thing we did that worked really well

00:36:18.159 --> 00:36:22.439
was we went and found all of the analytics people

00:36:22.439 --> 00:36:24.199
throughout the company, not just data scientists,

00:36:24.199 --> 00:36:26.639
not just people in IT, people in supply chain,

00:36:26.639 --> 00:36:29.840
people in sales, people in the regional finance offices,

00:36:30.639 --> 00:36:33.600
the people who are doing sort of amazing things,

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:37.000
often in something like Excel or Tableau.

00:36:37.959 --> 00:36:41.040
And we just gave them a count.

00:36:41.040 --> 00:36:43.120
We set up their connections they needed,

00:36:44.239 --> 00:36:46.840
gave them a brief overview of how to get started

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:47.919
and let them go.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.560
We went talking to a lot of the IT people

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:55.000
with this idea, they weren't terribly into it.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:58.199
There's always sort of concerns for security

00:36:59.159 --> 00:37:00.479
managing access and doing that.

00:37:00.479 --> 00:37:03.000
But I think we knew it was the right thing to do

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.360
to just get people using the tool.

00:37:05.360 --> 00:37:09.399
I attached myself to a project

00:37:09.399 --> 00:37:12.560
building a rather complex application in Shiny,

00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:17.560
sort of a crud tool that interacts with our promotional data.

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:24.280
Another member of our team actually built our,

00:37:24.280 --> 00:37:25.840
at the beginning of COVID,

00:37:25.840 --> 00:37:30.040
built the entire COVID tracking for our factories,

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:35.040
which anytime an employee either obviously contracts COVID

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:38.520
or reports that they've been in contact with someone,

00:37:38.520 --> 00:37:40.080
we needed to maintain this.

00:37:40.080 --> 00:37:42.000
Now, if you think back a year ago,

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:43.919
sort of the confusion around all this,

00:37:43.919 --> 00:37:47.600
like built the entire tool, built some security for it,

00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:49.919
sort of did all this in Shiny.

00:37:49.919 --> 00:37:52.719
And I think this really sold everyone

00:37:52.719 --> 00:37:54.280
that this is the route to go.

00:37:56.639 --> 00:37:59.000
Now, unfortunately, we didn't have any user groups

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:03.120
or any connections between all these separate people.

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:08.120
So we quickly had a lot of searches on Google

00:38:08.879 --> 00:38:13.280
on how to do things and some inconsistency

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:14.879
in the libraries people were using.

00:38:14.879 --> 00:38:17.439
And we were managing the library centrally,

00:38:17.439 --> 00:38:22.439
so we'd get all these requests for depreciated libraries

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:24.120
and have to manage all these.

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:26.800
So what we're trying to do now

00:38:27.679 --> 00:38:31.040
is actually have a group of people

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:32.840
who meet to share what they do

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:35.040
and sort of standardize some processes.

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.239
Not that we don't want people to be innovative

00:38:37.239 --> 00:38:38.080
or anything like that,

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:40.479
but there was just sort of a lot of work,

00:38:41.800 --> 00:38:44.040
managing people doing very similar things

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:45.639
in different ways.

00:38:49.399 --> 00:38:51.840
And then the final thing is we really, really pushed

00:38:51.840 --> 00:38:54.439
the idea of having a centralized analytics platform.

00:38:55.639 --> 00:38:57.360
That was cloud-based,

00:38:57.360 --> 00:38:59.719
that if you want to deliver content to someone,

00:38:59.719 --> 00:39:01.879
it was one place they could go to.

00:39:01.879 --> 00:39:04.320
It was web-based, everyone could access it.

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:06.399
If you remember, it was sort of the push

00:39:06.399 --> 00:39:08.439
for the cloud, mobile API.

00:39:09.399 --> 00:39:12.560
Mobile last year sort of dropped off the radar.

00:39:12.560 --> 00:39:15.120
I assume it's because everyone was working at home,

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:17.479
but the idea of the centralized platform

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:20.120
on a cloud-based architecture

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:23.479
really enabled us to go through 2020

00:39:23.479 --> 00:39:27.199
without any real delays in the work we were doing

00:39:27.199 --> 00:39:28.840
because we sort of had this stood up

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:30.280
right at the beginning.

00:39:30.280 --> 00:39:31.760
We worked through a lot of the issues

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:32.919
sort of in the middle of 2020,

00:39:32.919 --> 00:39:37.479
but having this enabled us to handle all these new things.

00:39:37.479 --> 00:39:39.120
Obviously we work in the,

00:39:39.120 --> 00:39:42.080
I don't know if anyone else is in sort of the CPG business,

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:45.080
but, or I guess if anyone was shopping at a grocery store,

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:49.280
you notice this, there were massive supply constraints.

00:39:49.600 --> 00:39:52.959
Most likely a lot of promotions were pulled

00:39:52.959 --> 00:39:54.040
that were planned.

00:39:55.199 --> 00:39:57.600
The way we allocated our production

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:01.919
was really to fill shelves versus anything else.

00:40:02.959 --> 00:40:06.719
All this stuff was sort of built in our studio

00:40:06.719 --> 00:40:08.360
and delivered through Connect.

00:40:09.320 --> 00:40:12.040
So everyone is sort of on board at this point.

00:40:13.959 --> 00:40:18.520
Unfortunately, the people we didn't sort of bring

00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:19.959
into this initial cohort

00:40:22.159 --> 00:40:24.800
were being asked to build things in R

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:27.399
without really knowing anything about R.

00:40:29.159 --> 00:40:32.919
So I think this is another problem of success

00:40:32.919 --> 00:40:35.080
sort of causing an issue.

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:38.120
We're trying to rectify this now,

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:40.120
we're really taking, Katie will know,

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:44.120
I routinely emailed her throughout the year last year

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:45.679
saying I really wanted to make sure

00:40:46.639 --> 00:40:49.239
we've got an education thing going.

00:40:49.239 --> 00:40:51.719
Entirely my fault that it never really took off.

00:40:51.719 --> 00:40:55.040
Now we're very, very, very committed to doing this.

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:56.560
We wanna upscale tons of people,

00:40:56.560 --> 00:40:58.959
we wanna give people these tools,

00:40:58.959 --> 00:41:00.560
we wanna see what people can do.

00:41:01.919 --> 00:41:03.120
Even today we're going through

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:05.439
sort of an architecture change.

00:41:05.439 --> 00:41:08.199
I was talking to some consultants

00:41:08.199 --> 00:41:11.040
who are managing migration of some things from SAS to R

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:17.040
and they sort of asked about scheduling, like batch jobs.

00:41:18.479 --> 00:41:20.239
And I took them through this idea

00:41:20.239 --> 00:41:22.399
of building an R Markdown file

00:41:22.399 --> 00:41:27.399
that runs on a schedule, generates a report,

00:41:27.919 --> 00:41:31.159
emails people sort of the changes made in the system.

00:41:31.159 --> 00:41:33.679
I think when people started to see this,

00:41:33.679 --> 00:41:35.320
I mean, they really see the power,

00:41:35.320 --> 00:41:36.560
now it's up to us to sort of make sure

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:37.840
they have the capability.

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:40.800
But I went really, really fast

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:42.080
because I know we're behind.

00:41:42.080 --> 00:41:44.120
Hopefully that gives enough time.

00:41:44.120 --> 00:41:45.080
Please ask questions.

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:48.840
You're welcome to email me or on LinkedIn,

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:52.919
however you can get ahold of me if you wanna talk more.

00:41:52.919 --> 00:41:54.679
I left out a lot of details on the architecture

00:41:54.679 --> 00:41:56.600
because I don't think you're supposed

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:57.520
to put your architecture up

00:41:57.520 --> 00:41:59.199
just in case there's any competitors.

00:41:59.199 --> 00:42:03.760
But if anyone wants to talk in depth, please let me know.

00:42:03.760 --> 00:42:04.600
Thank you.

00:42:08.199 --> 00:42:09.040
Awesome.

00:42:09.040 --> 00:42:10.199
Thank you so much, Phil.

00:42:12.040 --> 00:42:13.439
Oh, Katie, I'll let you go.

00:42:13.439 --> 00:42:14.280
Sorry.

00:42:15.760 --> 00:42:16.600
Thank you, Phil.

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:19.919
I think a lot of the challenges that you described

00:42:19.919 --> 00:42:22.760
are pretty common either in full

00:42:22.760 --> 00:42:24.399
or in pieces for a lot of folks.

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:27.000
So again, I'll encourage folks

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.399
to put questions in the chat window

00:42:29.399 --> 00:42:30.520
just for the sake of time

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:33.199
because I'm really eager as well

00:42:33.199 --> 00:42:36.800
to have you hear what Yuheng Chang has to say.

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:39.800
Yuheng joins us from Agco

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:43.080
and has a great app that she's chosen

00:42:43.080 --> 00:42:44.479
to spotlight with us today.

00:42:48.239 --> 00:42:50.000
Hey, I'm going to share my screen.

00:42:56.719 --> 00:42:58.040
Can you see my screen now?

00:42:59.000 --> 00:42:59.840
Yes, we can see it.

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:01.199
Yes.

00:43:01.199 --> 00:43:03.040
Okay, great.

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:03.879
So.

00:43:06.919 --> 00:43:08.679
So my name is Yuheng Chang.

00:43:08.679 --> 00:43:12.639
My background is actually in aerospace engineering

00:43:12.639 --> 00:43:13.959
and statistics.

00:43:13.959 --> 00:43:17.360
And after graduation, I had a great opportunity

00:43:17.360 --> 00:43:21.080
to join a fantastic team at Agco.

00:43:21.080 --> 00:43:24.959
And now I'm the advanced analytics specialist

00:43:24.959 --> 00:43:28.600
at global quality field in Agco.

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:33.360
So today I will quickly go through,

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:37.120
give you an overview about our company

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:42.120
because that will help you to understand our challenges

00:43:42.479 --> 00:43:46.360
and the difficulties we are facing right now

00:43:46.360 --> 00:43:51.360
because I believe most of you have ever,

00:43:51.800 --> 00:43:55.719
probably everyone has ever had Kellogg's product,

00:43:55.719 --> 00:43:58.760
you know, their food or the flight,

00:43:58.760 --> 00:44:01.000
either Airbus or Boeing,

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.560
you know, they both use present with these engines.

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:06.159
So you sort of have your customer experiences

00:44:06.159 --> 00:44:07.760
with their products,

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:12.560
but I believe probably no one has ever used our product

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:14.639
before, I mean, neither do I.

00:44:14.639 --> 00:44:18.479
But I believe many of you have had the food,

00:44:18.479 --> 00:44:23.479
you know, either plant or harvested by our product.

00:44:24.719 --> 00:44:29.280
So we are, we are a global leader in the design,

00:44:29.479 --> 00:44:32.719
manufactured and distribution for agricultural solutions.

00:44:32.719 --> 00:44:35.040
And we are also the leader and experts

00:44:35.040 --> 00:44:36.919
in global quality solutions.

00:44:36.919 --> 00:44:41.479
So these are the four big leading brands we have

00:44:41.479 --> 00:44:44.239
for different type of agriculture vehicles,

00:44:44.239 --> 00:44:47.479
including tractors, rogators, surrogators,

00:44:47.479 --> 00:44:50.000
and anything you name it.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:55.000
But we are also the only full one product

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:58.800
in company in agriculture industry.

00:44:59.320 --> 00:45:00.159
Why I say that?

00:45:00.159 --> 00:45:02.959
Because we also has a very comprehensive

00:45:02.959 --> 00:45:05.800
grain and protein department,

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:08.399
which we own these five brands.

00:45:08.399 --> 00:45:12.399
So you probably know GSI and also CNBRA

00:45:14.719 --> 00:45:17.600
and other brands as well.

00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:20.919
So our values and mission stand on, you know,

00:45:20.919 --> 00:45:25.879
providing sustainability and good quality products

00:45:25.879 --> 00:45:29.040
to farmers and also improving farm income.

00:45:31.239 --> 00:45:34.919
So just a quick overview to our history.

00:45:34.919 --> 00:45:39.639
As you can see, Agco is a pretty young company.

00:45:39.639 --> 00:45:42.600
Last year was our 30 years anniversary.

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:46.199
And we officially started in 1990.

00:45:46.199 --> 00:45:48.000
And in the past 30 years,

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.560
actually we have acquired over 40 companies.

00:45:51.560 --> 00:45:54.280
That's why, that's one of the method

00:45:54.600 --> 00:45:58.679
we grow this company so fast and now become so big.

00:45:58.679 --> 00:46:03.679
And during, you know, acquiring other acquisition

00:46:03.760 --> 00:46:08.760
and, you know, it means you have to also acquire

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:12.840
that company's data vault as well.

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:16.800
It means we kept gather other people's data vault

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:18.320
into our own system.

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:22.159
That make our data actually very dirty.

00:46:22.159 --> 00:46:24.080
I mean, more complex than, you know,

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:27.760
the CFD turbine flow data I've ever handled before.

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:31.879
And that actually caused a lot of challenges to us,

00:46:31.879 --> 00:46:35.239
especially for agriculture.

00:46:35.239 --> 00:46:38.360
Even let's talk about tractors.

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:40.439
Even you see different type of tractors

00:46:40.439 --> 00:46:43.280
doesn't mean we can really just compare them together

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:47.840
because we have tractors designed for the maybe common uses.

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:50.639
And also we have tractors designed for vineyard.

00:46:50.639 --> 00:46:53.560
We have tractors designed for grants or for fruit.

00:46:53.560 --> 00:46:58.040
So how to standardize our analysis tool

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:02.239
to make sure when we analyze our data,

00:47:02.239 --> 00:47:05.479
when we analyze our product quality,

00:47:05.479 --> 00:47:08.399
we won't make mistakes like comparing apples

00:47:08.399 --> 00:47:09.959
and oranges together.

00:47:09.959 --> 00:47:13.479
And we can provide nice, you know, KPI for everyone,

00:47:13.479 --> 00:47:17.639
especially now Acco produce, you know,

00:47:17.639 --> 00:47:21.560
133,000 vehicles per year.

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:25.959
And we have 43 manufacturing locations.

00:47:25.959 --> 00:47:28.159
And in the past, you know,

00:47:28.159 --> 00:47:30.120
some of the manufacturing locations

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:34.760
were joined by acquisition.

00:47:34.760 --> 00:47:39.399
So it means each factories actually has their habits,

00:47:39.399 --> 00:47:40.479
their know-how.

00:47:40.479 --> 00:47:45.000
So we have to understand, you know,

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:47.040
what they have and what they try to do.

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:50.919
And also make sure when we standardize this system,

00:47:50.919 --> 00:47:53.000
we can balance everything.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.320
And we can try to make everyone, you know,

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:56.959
not only our engineers happy,

00:47:56.959 --> 00:47:58.719
but also make our customers happy.

00:48:01.199 --> 00:48:06.199
And by 2020, actually we have 3,275 providers

00:48:07.239 --> 00:48:10.199
and our products and customers are, you know,

00:48:10.199 --> 00:48:11.840
spreading worldwide.

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:14.679
And we produce not only, you know, tractors,

00:48:14.679 --> 00:48:18.360
irrigators and different type of, you know,

00:48:18.360 --> 00:48:19.679
or grain storage.

00:48:19.679 --> 00:48:23.399
We also produce, you know, grain products as well.

00:48:23.399 --> 00:48:26.520
So this is about Acco.

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:30.959
And now we're talking about what do we do with R,

00:48:30.959 --> 00:48:34.239
what we choose R and what are our challenges?

00:48:34.239 --> 00:48:37.159
So one of the reason we choose R,

00:48:37.159 --> 00:48:40.000
or you can say we choose RStudio and RStudio Connect

00:48:40.040 --> 00:48:42.919
because it provides a very,

00:48:44.399 --> 00:48:46.080
to me, it's a very friendly environment

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:48.520
and also very nice flexibility

00:48:48.520 --> 00:48:51.840
for us to customize any tools we want.

00:48:53.840 --> 00:48:56.800
So our challenge is, you know,

00:48:56.800 --> 00:48:59.959
Labyrinth data science to supercharge

00:48:59.959 --> 00:49:01.479
global quality control.

00:49:01.479 --> 00:49:06.479
So let me use this map to go through our design map.

00:49:07.040 --> 00:49:11.360
So to us in data, you know, in data science field,

00:49:11.360 --> 00:49:16.360
our wonderland is the data pool with puzzles,

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:19.879
which are, you know, the market dynamics,

00:49:19.879 --> 00:49:24.040
product qualities, customers' experiences and so forth.

00:49:24.040 --> 00:49:26.399
And our adventure starts at the moment

00:49:26.399 --> 00:49:30.520
we first exam our data and try to find a way out, right?

00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:32.520
That's what Alice tried to do.

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:37.520
And when we discover and explore our market dynamics,

00:49:37.560 --> 00:49:40.120
then we start to do our product design.

00:49:40.120 --> 00:49:43.199
That's the first phase of our R&D.

00:49:43.199 --> 00:49:47.639
And then we do tech development, try to finish R&D.

00:49:47.639 --> 00:49:51.919
And then once we finish up, we start to make products.

00:49:51.919 --> 00:49:54.000
And then we do test.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:58.159
And after test, we deliver our products to our customers.

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:02.639
And after a while, we start to receive feedback.

00:50:02.639 --> 00:50:06.120
And like all the companies we got,

00:50:06.120 --> 00:50:09.639
angel customers who love our products for all reasons.

00:50:09.639 --> 00:50:11.520
And sometimes we have, you know,

00:50:14.439 --> 00:50:18.439
just, you know, unhappy customers.

00:50:18.439 --> 00:50:21.239
Yeah, I won't say crazy customers, but unhappy customers.

00:50:21.239 --> 00:50:23.520
And when they find out, you know,

00:50:23.520 --> 00:50:26.080
that the products are not as good as they expected,

00:50:26.080 --> 00:50:28.159
they file plans or, you know,

00:50:28.159 --> 00:50:31.280
the product is failed too fast, we receive plans.

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:35.760
So let's build better customer experiences.

00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:39.280
And our goal is to make everybody happy

00:50:39.280 --> 00:50:42.760
and try to improve our customer experiences.

00:50:42.760 --> 00:50:47.600
So some people may ask, what do we do during R&D?

00:50:47.600 --> 00:50:52.600
Because, you know, one chain in quality control is R&D.

00:50:53.360 --> 00:50:57.239
And in automobile industry or in aerospace industry,

00:50:57.239 --> 00:50:58.879
actually in agriculture industry,

00:50:58.879 --> 00:51:03.879
we all use DOE, which is design experiment a lot.

00:51:03.959 --> 00:51:08.239
But for agriculture, most of the time we use that

00:51:08.239 --> 00:51:13.080
for like do some scientific way to do plants.

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:17.360
But it's a little bit hard to use design experiment methods

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:20.840
in agriculture machine building

00:51:20.840 --> 00:51:24.040
because unlike automobile,

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:26.760
you can predict which environment

00:51:26.760 --> 00:51:28.879
your car may experience, right?

00:51:28.879 --> 00:51:32.120
I mean, the road, we know the average quality of road.

00:51:32.120 --> 00:51:35.080
We know we have highway, we have just regular road

00:51:35.080 --> 00:51:39.520
or sometimes pretty muddy and we know traffic lights

00:51:39.520 --> 00:51:44.520
and we know the probably average driver habits.

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:50.520
But for agriculture, we have very, very, you know,

00:51:50.959 --> 00:51:55.959
over varieties of geography characteristics.

00:51:56.679 --> 00:51:58.479
You know, the machine could be used

00:51:58.479 --> 00:52:01.840
for very, very cold environment

00:52:01.840 --> 00:52:05.399
or very, very hot environment or very muddy environment

00:52:05.399 --> 00:52:08.159
and also different plants.

00:52:08.159 --> 00:52:11.879
And we cannot just design one harvester

00:52:11.879 --> 00:52:13.760
for all type of plants.

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:17.360
And also we have different climate.

00:52:17.360 --> 00:52:22.360
So it's a little bit like too many elements to DOE plus

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:27.879
when automobile industry do test driving

00:52:27.879 --> 00:52:29.040
for their new product,

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:32.600
they can build their own campus and just do test driving.

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:36.360
But to us, when we do our test driving,

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:40.000
it's either plant something or harvest something.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.439
And when you harvest out the plant,

00:52:42.439 --> 00:52:46.719
it means you got nothing left to do more experiments.

00:52:46.719 --> 00:52:51.040
So that's one of our challenge and also dilemma.

00:52:51.040 --> 00:52:55.800
So it means for our product design and technology develop,

00:52:55.800 --> 00:52:57.919
DOE method is pretty limited.

00:52:57.919 --> 00:53:02.919
So it depends a lot in the, you know, plant analysis.

00:53:04.959 --> 00:53:09.959
So one solution to us is to develop a centralized tool,

00:53:10.159 --> 00:53:13.360
providing information and comprehensive insight

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:15.199
of data analysis.

00:53:15.199 --> 00:53:19.199
So we have several methods

00:53:19.199 --> 00:53:22.959
and the first method is to standardize

00:53:22.959 --> 00:53:26.560
our performance measurements,

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:30.479
such as claim rate and repair frequency.

00:53:30.479 --> 00:53:35.479
And everybody has to use the same methods to do the math.

00:53:35.639 --> 00:53:39.399
Otherwise we cannot put all the numbers on the same page.

00:53:39.840 --> 00:53:41.000
And also we have to use the same way

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:44.479
to do cost and usage, our analysis.

00:53:44.479 --> 00:53:48.080
And also we have different type of KPIs

00:53:48.080 --> 00:53:50.719
to measure different type of things.

00:53:50.719 --> 00:53:54.120
And the second thing is we recently

00:53:55.159 --> 00:53:57.360
start to integrate telemetry data,

00:53:57.360 --> 00:54:02.360
which means we can monitor our machines life.

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:09.280
And we sort of, I think we receive data from each machine

00:54:10.239 --> 00:54:13.679
sometimes every five seconds, sometimes every 10 seconds.

00:54:13.679 --> 00:54:15.600
And what does it mean?

00:54:15.600 --> 00:54:17.360
It means we've got different type of code

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:19.000
and when we receive the code,

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:22.080
doesn't mean the machine failed.

00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:24.639
It could be something, it could be nothing.

00:54:24.639 --> 00:54:27.280
So we need to try to understand,

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:30.719
you can say the language machines try to tell us.

00:54:30.719 --> 00:54:33.560
And also we need to set up a threshold,

00:54:33.560 --> 00:54:38.560
like if we analyze telemetry data every single time,

00:54:38.560 --> 00:54:41.479
it means every 10 seconds is huge amount of information

00:54:41.479 --> 00:54:43.439
and maybe too much.

00:54:43.439 --> 00:54:45.120
If we set a threshold like,

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:48.159
okay, we only get data like every 60 seconds,

00:54:48.159 --> 00:54:49.080
maybe that's enough.

00:54:49.080 --> 00:54:52.040
Or we have to do just every 100 seconds.

00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:54.320
So that's the part we are developing

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:57.080
and try to figure out what's the best way

00:54:57.080 --> 00:55:01.360
to set up threshold code and focus on different brand,

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:03.399
different machine and probably

00:55:04.399 --> 00:55:06.760
under different user environments.

00:55:07.639 --> 00:55:08.879
And once we figure it out,

00:55:08.879 --> 00:55:11.800
we can build an alarm system to forecast failure.

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:16.280
Means we notice, okay, some code keep coming out,

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:19.600
means some part will fail out.

00:55:19.600 --> 00:55:23.560
So we can notice our farmer say,

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:26.280
hey, maybe the O-ring in your engine,

00:55:26.280 --> 00:55:30.080
which part is going to, you need to replace that.

00:55:30.080 --> 00:55:33.639
Otherwise it will fail maybe in the next 10 usage hours,

00:55:33.639 --> 00:55:34.479
something like that.

00:55:34.479 --> 00:55:38.159
So farmers can replace that before the machine fails.

00:55:38.159 --> 00:55:41.560
So the farmers won't, got nothing to do

00:55:41.560 --> 00:55:46.560
and just with the time for his work.

00:55:48.719 --> 00:55:50.760
And then the third thing is

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:57.840
to build a predictive model to predict failure rate.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:01.760
Here we use Weibull analysis.

00:56:01.760 --> 00:56:05.479
So some people probably heard about Weibull before

00:56:05.479 --> 00:56:07.919
because it's a very mature method,

00:56:07.919 --> 00:56:12.479
has been applied in manufacturing industry

00:56:12.479 --> 00:56:15.439
for I think since 1970s.

00:56:15.439 --> 00:56:16.919
But in the past 50 years,

00:56:16.919 --> 00:56:19.679
actually Weibull analysis has been improved

00:56:19.679 --> 00:56:22.159
and modified into different forms.

00:56:22.159 --> 00:56:26.280
And we applied this method over 20 years ago

00:56:26.280 --> 00:56:28.199
and we kept modifying that.

00:56:28.199 --> 00:56:31.439
And in our latest tool,

00:56:31.439 --> 00:56:36.439
we built in one is you can say empirical method.

00:56:36.639 --> 00:56:40.120
Another one is based on maximum likelihood method

00:56:40.120 --> 00:56:45.120
because it depends on which way we collect the data

00:56:45.280 --> 00:56:47.280
and use some different scenarios.

00:56:48.439 --> 00:56:51.080
And the last thing is other data source

00:56:51.080 --> 00:56:52.719
and the basic extensions.

00:56:52.719 --> 00:56:57.479
And like for every time we receive a claim,

00:56:57.520 --> 00:56:59.719
it comes with one global causal part.

00:56:59.719 --> 00:57:03.280
So one main part they'll sometimes come with

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:08.000
very few replaced part or hundreds of replaced part.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:08.840
Are they related?

00:57:08.840 --> 00:57:10.600
Can we find out some patterns?

00:57:10.600 --> 00:57:13.520
That's also our job.

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:15.080
We try to figure it out.

00:57:15.080 --> 00:57:16.840
So the major challenge,

00:57:16.840 --> 00:57:20.439
like I said a few minutes ago,

00:57:20.439 --> 00:57:22.199
first is dirty data.

00:57:22.199 --> 00:57:25.120
Because during M&A,

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:29.040
we kept receiving data from different companies

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:31.959
and each company has its own habits

00:57:31.959 --> 00:57:34.600
to collect the data, to store the data.

00:57:34.600 --> 00:57:38.040
So we have to put that into our central ETL system.

00:57:38.040 --> 00:57:40.760
So when ETL received that,

00:57:40.760 --> 00:57:44.320
and then after a while,

00:57:44.320 --> 00:57:47.760
I got everything actually still very dirty.

00:57:47.760 --> 00:57:51.479
So we have to figure out a way to claim it

00:57:51.479 --> 00:57:56.479
without hurting important information inside the data.

00:57:57.439 --> 00:58:00.320
And then is the limited sample size.

00:58:00.320 --> 00:58:01.600
And like I said,

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:05.439
in agriculture,

00:58:05.439 --> 00:58:08.320
we won't be able to do that type of,

00:58:09.239 --> 00:58:13.520
a lot of tests like automobile industry do.

00:58:13.520 --> 00:58:17.360
So in certain way, our sample size is limited,

00:58:17.360 --> 00:58:19.879
but doesn't mean that the data size is limited.

00:58:19.919 --> 00:58:21.280
We got huge data size,

00:58:21.280 --> 00:58:23.919
just the sample size somehow is limited.

00:58:23.919 --> 00:58:28.280
And also we have unpredictable product usage.

00:58:31.080 --> 00:58:33.560
Even if the same product,

00:58:33.560 --> 00:58:35.520
but when we sell it to different,

00:58:35.520 --> 00:58:37.080
let's say in the United States,

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:39.560
but different states and different areas,

00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:44.560
different farmers have different usage preference.

00:58:45.159 --> 00:58:49.040
And also they probably use them for different purposes.

00:58:49.040 --> 00:58:50.439
So the product usage

00:58:50.439 --> 00:58:53.159
actually is a little bit unpredictable.

00:58:53.159 --> 00:58:58.159
And also this tool we build has to be,

00:59:00.679 --> 00:59:04.360
work with big data and life data.

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:06.800
We have to monitor telemetry data,

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:08.479
congregate everything together.

00:59:08.479 --> 00:59:12.639
Also our users hope everything can be calculated

00:59:12.639 --> 00:59:13.719
in real time.

00:59:13.719 --> 00:59:16.639
So it means we need something to help us

00:59:16.639 --> 00:59:18.639
to organize everything.

00:59:18.639 --> 00:59:21.040
And every time we choose different filters

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:23.639
and the filters has to be fully dynamic,

00:59:23.639 --> 00:59:25.040
we can get different results

00:59:25.040 --> 00:59:27.040
and the results has to be reliable.

00:59:27.040 --> 00:59:28.840
So those are our main challenges.

00:59:28.840 --> 00:59:33.280
And that's the main reason we choose to work with R

00:59:33.280 --> 00:59:35.159
and also RStudio Connect,

00:59:35.159 --> 00:59:38.600
because after we build the user interface,

00:59:38.600 --> 00:59:43.600
we store everything on our SQL server.

00:59:44.600 --> 00:59:47.159
And all we have to do is send the message to,

00:59:47.159 --> 00:59:50.199
script to SQL and then tell SQL

00:59:50.199 --> 00:59:51.719
which part of the data we need.

00:59:51.719 --> 00:59:53.760
And if it's small amount of data,

00:59:53.760 --> 00:59:55.080
maybe just a few seconds,

00:59:55.080 --> 00:59:56.399
if it's a huge amount of data,

00:59:56.399 --> 00:59:58.639
maybe up to 20 to 30 seconds,

00:59:58.639 --> 01:00:00.600
but still acceptable.

01:00:00.600 --> 01:00:05.280
But another important thing is this tool can be used for,

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:07.679
by multiple users at the same time.

01:00:07.679 --> 01:00:12.679
So before we start working with R,

01:00:12.919 --> 01:00:14.719
this is our first generation tool.

01:00:14.719 --> 01:00:18.080
We call AIDA, same name as the famous opera,

01:00:18.080 --> 01:00:19.800
you know, Princess AIDA.

01:00:19.800 --> 01:00:23.520
And this tool was built under Tableau

01:00:23.520 --> 01:00:28.520
and Tableau is a very beautiful tool for presentation,

01:00:28.639 --> 01:00:32.520
but we did have a lot of hard time to work with that

01:00:32.520 --> 01:00:35.320
when we, you know, the data got bigger, bigger and bigger.

01:00:35.320 --> 01:00:38.600
Plus it's not easy to integrate

01:00:38.600 --> 01:00:42.439
some complicated math algorithms

01:00:43.120 --> 01:00:44.719
to calculate everything in real time.

01:00:44.719 --> 01:00:48.040
So eventually we just compromised.

01:00:48.040 --> 01:00:51.199
We pre-calculate a lot of things.

01:00:51.199 --> 01:00:55.520
So even everything we pre-calculated, you know, every day,

01:00:55.520 --> 01:00:58.080
but pre-calculation means

01:00:58.080 --> 01:01:01.360
we have very limited permutation combination.

01:01:01.360 --> 01:01:05.080
We cannot really get what user really want.

01:01:05.080 --> 01:01:09.719
So eventually we go to R and build this tool.

01:01:09.719 --> 01:01:11.639
We call that Analyticus.

01:01:11.679 --> 01:01:14.479
And this is a simplified version.

01:01:14.479 --> 01:01:17.159
And this is the main copy, as you can see.

01:01:17.159 --> 01:01:21.919
And I'm going to just give you a tour to Analyticus.

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:29.439
So this is the homepage and don't worry,

01:01:29.439 --> 01:01:30.840
you won't be able to use that

01:01:30.840 --> 01:01:35.399
because you have to have our VPN to access to this website.

01:01:35.399 --> 01:01:37.879
And this is just a quick demo to you.

01:01:37.879 --> 01:01:42.879
So, like I say, everything is dynamic,

01:01:43.600 --> 01:01:48.600
means if I choose, you know, different type of machine,

01:01:48.639 --> 01:01:50.919
they will go through and this is default.

01:01:50.919 --> 01:01:54.919
So it means we got all the manufacturing location together.

01:01:54.919 --> 01:01:59.360
And here, all I want to do, let's say tractors.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:01.879
I don't want, you know, harvesting, you know,

01:02:01.879 --> 01:02:05.120
different type of or implements or generators.

01:02:05.159 --> 01:02:08.320
And then we have a lot of manufacturing locations

01:02:08.320 --> 01:02:13.320
and this is my dummy data, one of my dummy data.

01:02:14.239 --> 01:02:18.600
And I got so many dummy tractors here

01:02:18.600 --> 01:02:23.600
and let's just do, because I know we're running

01:02:24.040 --> 01:02:28.239
out of time a little bit, so just do something simple.

01:02:28.239 --> 01:02:33.239
And here I choose analysis level, you know,

01:02:36.520 --> 01:02:38.520
from global cost of part number

01:02:38.520 --> 01:02:41.479
and to failure area to failure feedback.

01:02:41.479 --> 01:02:43.679
And actually this is the highest level

01:02:43.679 --> 01:02:48.679
and this is the sub area and this is the sub sub area.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:51.399
And in the past, we usually just focus

01:02:51.399 --> 01:02:53.439
on global cost of part number,

01:02:53.439 --> 01:02:56.159
but then we figured out sometimes, you know,

01:02:56.560 --> 01:02:59.719
it's not about global cost of part.

01:02:59.719 --> 01:03:03.399
It's more about some area, just easy to get failed.

01:03:03.399 --> 01:03:07.239
So we try to, you know, use different way to figure out

01:03:08.199 --> 01:03:13.199
what's the prediction, sorry, the failure rate

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:17.840
using different way to evaluate our Weibo analysis.

01:03:17.840 --> 01:03:20.800
So first we got like data overall information

01:03:20.800 --> 01:03:24.320
and you can monitor your data by, you know,

01:03:24.320 --> 01:03:26.360
choosing this people table

01:03:26.360 --> 01:03:29.560
and this is our other indicator.

01:03:29.560 --> 01:03:33.399
And this is our alarm list showing us something

01:03:33.399 --> 01:03:38.399
like summary and we probably want to go from, for example,

01:03:39.479 --> 01:03:42.320
we always try to know what's our failure rate

01:03:42.320 --> 01:03:44.040
at our target hour.

01:03:44.040 --> 01:03:48.840
And previously we said our target hour is 1000 engine hour

01:03:48.840 --> 01:03:51.479
and say at 1000, the failure rate

01:03:51.639 --> 01:03:54.120
for these two already be 100%

01:03:54.120 --> 01:03:57.239
and probably reach this number way before 1000.

01:03:57.239 --> 01:04:00.280
And we usually want to keep this number, you know,

01:04:00.280 --> 01:04:01.919
as small as we want.

01:04:01.919 --> 01:04:04.760
And this is the full Weibo information.

01:04:04.760 --> 01:04:08.080
And the Weibo plot actually look like this.

01:04:10.479 --> 01:04:14.719
Okay, so if we choose global cost of part number,

01:04:16.719 --> 01:04:19.159
you can see this one is about hose

01:04:19.159 --> 01:04:22.800
and we also want to see maybe we got,

01:04:22.800 --> 01:04:25.280
okay, that's only hose we got.

01:04:25.280 --> 01:04:27.959
And we got air pressure.

01:04:27.959 --> 01:04:30.239
We want to see what's going on here.

01:04:30.239 --> 01:04:32.600
And for air pressure, it could be,

01:04:32.600 --> 01:04:35.600
let's assume we got a lot of points here

01:04:35.600 --> 01:04:40.479
and only a few, you know, in low usage hour.

01:04:40.479 --> 01:04:42.560
We may just, you know, for some time,

01:04:42.560 --> 01:04:44.879
we probably want to see what's going on

01:04:44.879 --> 01:04:46.399
when we just cut off our data

01:04:46.399 --> 01:04:49.080
because some of them could be outliers.

01:04:49.879 --> 01:04:51.959
And you probably notice the number change.

01:04:51.959 --> 01:04:55.879
And this is the total failure number also change.

01:04:55.879 --> 01:05:00.360
And the way we calculate the total machines covered by,

01:05:00.360 --> 01:05:02.719
you know, this global cost of part number

01:05:02.719 --> 01:05:05.399
sometimes also change because it has to be covered

01:05:05.399 --> 01:05:08.080
by the manufacturing date range.

01:05:08.080 --> 01:05:11.560
So beta is very important because if this number,

01:05:11.560 --> 01:05:13.840
you know, equal, I mean, larger than one,

01:05:13.840 --> 01:05:16.719
it means it basically worn out by time.

01:05:16.719 --> 01:05:19.600
So we always hope this, you know,

01:05:21.760 --> 01:05:24.120
can be, you know, larger than one.

01:05:24.120 --> 01:05:24.959
Okay.

01:05:26.199 --> 01:05:27.040
And,

01:05:30.320 --> 01:05:32.520
sorry, Rachel, I couldn't see,

01:05:32.520 --> 01:05:34.159
I see you raise your hand, but.

01:05:34.159 --> 01:05:35.800
Oh, sorry.

01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:37.679
I was trying to give a one minute warning

01:05:37.679 --> 01:05:40.639
in the easiest way possible.

01:05:42.080 --> 01:05:45.679
And yeah, and also you can download data

01:05:45.679 --> 01:05:48.120
and everything very fast.

01:05:48.120 --> 01:05:52.479
And these are just more charts and like heat map,

01:05:52.479 --> 01:05:55.280
everything, and you can, you know,

01:05:55.280 --> 01:06:00.120
monitor things by different way and different region.

01:06:00.120 --> 01:06:01.040
That's it.

01:06:01.040 --> 01:06:04.159
And also one thing important to us

01:06:04.159 --> 01:06:07.040
is we can just download after, you know,

01:06:07.040 --> 01:06:08.080
selecting everything.

01:06:08.080 --> 01:06:10.560
We can also use the second layer filter to,

01:06:11.399 --> 01:06:14.159
this is a design to let them probably,

01:06:14.159 --> 01:06:16.000
they want to filter down a few things

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:18.479
and they can download the reports.

01:06:18.479 --> 01:06:21.679
And this is the example of the report I already generated

01:06:21.679 --> 01:06:24.600
because I know we probably will, you know,

01:06:24.600 --> 01:06:25.959
go out of time.

01:06:27.320 --> 01:06:29.000
Nothing like that.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:34.000
So overall, this is the tool we built.

01:06:34.399 --> 01:06:36.679
And actually there were a lot more functions

01:06:36.679 --> 01:06:39.040
for like predictions and analysis,

01:06:39.040 --> 01:06:42.600
but today we got a little bit running out of time.

01:06:42.600 --> 01:06:45.080
So I'm going to stop right here.

01:06:48.600 --> 01:06:49.439
Awesome.

01:06:49.439 --> 01:06:50.679
Thank you so much, Yuheng.

01:06:50.679 --> 01:06:53.679
It was great to see the application as well.

01:06:53.679 --> 01:06:55.320
I'm trying to scroll through

01:06:55.320 --> 01:06:57.639
and see if there were some questions there

01:06:57.639 --> 01:07:01.399
because I'd love to stay on and ask a few live questions

01:07:01.399 --> 01:07:02.879
to all three of our speakers,

01:07:02.879 --> 01:07:04.679
if anybody can stay on with us.

01:07:05.760 --> 01:07:08.320
But again, we will post the Q and A

01:07:08.320 --> 01:07:10.959
and the link to the recording on the meetup page

01:07:11.120 --> 01:07:13.800
and on community.rstudio.com.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:18.879
But Yuheng, one of the questions I see for you was,

01:07:20.760 --> 01:07:23.239
I'm trying, it's scrolling down here.

01:07:23.239 --> 01:07:27.439
If there were alternatives to Webull that you were using,

01:07:27.439 --> 01:07:29.800
and Jeff just mentioned that

01:07:29.800 --> 01:07:31.600
he may have missed a few of those.

01:07:33.320 --> 01:07:36.080
Alternative about what, sorry.

01:07:38.439 --> 01:07:40.879
I'm not sure if Jeff is still on.

01:07:41.840 --> 01:07:44.000
Were there any alternatives to Webull methods

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:47.879
that you looked at or did you just look at using Webull?

01:07:47.879 --> 01:07:48.719
Yes.

01:07:49.879 --> 01:07:51.520
Because basically,

01:07:54.120 --> 01:07:55.840
well, actually,

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:59.959
one thing I didn't have time to show is actually

01:07:59.959 --> 01:08:03.600
there are, we were focusing on different way

01:08:03.600 --> 01:08:05.800
to exploring Webull because like I say,

01:08:05.800 --> 01:08:09.399
there are several different ways to build a Webull data.

01:08:09.600 --> 01:08:13.360
But so far, we've tried like three different ways

01:08:13.360 --> 01:08:14.199
to build that.

01:08:14.199 --> 01:08:16.680
But other than Webull, we also try like,

01:08:18.640 --> 01:08:21.200
I mean, time-dependent Gaussian process,

01:08:21.200 --> 01:08:22.919
which I'm familiar with,

01:08:22.919 --> 01:08:27.839
and also other type of time series models.

01:08:27.839 --> 01:08:32.439
There are varieties, but they all have to be,

01:08:33.720 --> 01:08:36.200
I noticed if I want to get a good result,

01:08:36.200 --> 01:08:39.000
I have to utilize a lot of telemetry data

01:08:39.600 --> 01:08:40.759
or you can say live monitor data

01:08:40.759 --> 01:08:44.839
because those data will provide not only

01:08:46.879 --> 01:08:48.959
the information from claims.

01:08:48.959 --> 01:08:51.919
Because when we receive a claim means something broke

01:08:51.919 --> 01:08:54.600
and we collect everything like usage hours

01:08:54.600 --> 01:08:57.799
and all type of situations of that certain machine.

01:08:57.799 --> 01:09:02.319
But live data also providing us information like that

01:09:02.319 --> 01:09:04.359
when the machine is still healthy.

01:09:04.359 --> 01:09:07.720
So before we officially

01:09:09.479 --> 01:09:11.919
release other tools,

01:09:11.919 --> 01:09:14.319
we have to clear out telemetry data.

01:09:14.319 --> 01:09:16.080
And that's one of the challenge

01:09:16.080 --> 01:09:18.120
because currently we're facing

01:09:19.680 --> 01:09:22.040
first is the amount of the data issue.

01:09:22.040 --> 01:09:23.600
We try to find out what's the best way

01:09:23.600 --> 01:09:25.160
to set up a threshold.

01:09:25.160 --> 01:09:27.600
Otherwise, it's a little bit overwhelmed

01:09:27.600 --> 01:09:31.000
and probably won't make our predictive model

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:32.560
sensitive enough.

01:09:32.560 --> 01:09:33.879
That's one problem.

01:09:33.879 --> 01:09:37.240
Yeah, so there are other issues like

01:09:39.319 --> 01:09:43.279
what code we receive from telemetry data

01:09:43.279 --> 01:09:46.439
we should use to get into our predictive model.

01:09:46.439 --> 01:09:50.200
So that's why some predict model

01:09:50.200 --> 01:09:52.520
we haven't fully explored

01:09:52.520 --> 01:09:55.399
and also we haven't released this tool yet.

01:09:59.160 --> 01:10:00.640
Thank you, Yuhang.

01:10:00.640 --> 01:10:03.959
I think most of the questions to Brendan and Phil

01:10:03.959 --> 01:10:05.640
were maybe answered in the chat,

01:10:05.640 --> 01:10:08.040
but if there are any other questions

01:10:08.040 --> 01:10:09.799
that you'd like to ask them live,

01:10:09.799 --> 01:10:12.359
I'm happy to have you post them there

01:10:12.359 --> 01:10:14.479
or just ask out loud and unmute yourself.

01:10:22.040 --> 01:10:25.680
Or if you're thinking of other questions,

01:10:25.680 --> 01:10:29.120
I will go for one more for Yuhang.

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:30.879
I see Brendan had just asked,

01:10:30.879 --> 01:10:34.040
what were the reports you showed at the end

01:10:34.040 --> 01:10:37.839
shared directly with the customer, the machinery owner?

01:10:38.640 --> 01:10:41.479
This is our inside tool.

01:10:41.479 --> 01:10:45.080
So the reports are to our PCR engineers

01:10:45.080 --> 01:10:49.319
and also our manufacturing factories.

01:10:49.319 --> 01:10:51.520
And for customers, as I know,

01:10:51.520 --> 01:10:55.160
we have another system working with Salesforce

01:10:55.160 --> 01:10:58.200
generating different type of reports.

01:10:58.200 --> 01:11:03.200
So some information we only show to our people.

01:11:04.200 --> 01:11:05.040
So, yeah.

01:11:10.680 --> 01:11:11.720
Great, thank you.

01:11:12.640 --> 01:11:15.040
Are there any other questions that we missed?

01:11:19.160 --> 01:11:22.240
Oh, one other question from Josh, Yuhang.

01:11:22.240 --> 01:11:25.160
Did you encounter any internal conflict

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:29.720
or internal politics from using Shiny in place of Tableau?

01:11:30.720 --> 01:11:31.560
Yes.

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:35.799
We actually,

01:11:37.839 --> 01:11:39.479
I don't want to use the word fight,

01:11:39.479 --> 01:11:44.479
but we did spend quite a while to let IT department

01:11:46.479 --> 01:11:49.680
convince that Shiny is a good tool to be used

01:11:49.680 --> 01:11:51.799
because previously they really, really want us

01:11:51.799 --> 01:11:54.040
to stay with Tableau forever.

01:11:54.040 --> 01:11:58.000
And then we developed some cases,

01:11:58.959 --> 01:12:03.799
including I already spent time to build Weibo,

01:12:03.799 --> 01:12:07.160
actually two different type of Weibo inside Tableau

01:12:07.160 --> 01:12:08.520
to connect to live data

01:12:08.520 --> 01:12:11.759
and show them the turnaround time difference.

01:12:11.759 --> 01:12:15.000
And one's like five to 10 seconds the most.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:18.279
Another one is, forget about it.

01:12:18.279 --> 01:12:21.520
So very soon they realized, you know, Tableau is good.

01:12:21.520 --> 01:12:23.879
We still use that for a long scenario.

01:12:23.879 --> 01:12:25.959
Just for this type of case,

01:12:25.959 --> 01:12:28.080
we really need to switch to Shiny.

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:34.000
So yes, we did encounter some internal conflicts,

01:12:35.640 --> 01:12:39.120
but we solved it and now everybody happy.

